    description: "Samaria, the capital city of Israel's northern kingdom and a region inhabited by a mixed Israelite-foreign population following Assyrian deportations, became the locus of deep cultural and religious division between Jews and Samaritans that persisted into New Testament times and framed many of Jesus's teachings about radical inclusion and ethnic reconciliation. Omri's establishment of Samaria as the northern kingdom's capital (885 BC) transformed it into a significant political and cultural center, though Assyrian conquest and deportation policies (721 BC) left a genetically mixed population that developed distinct religious practices and their own version of the Torah, creating an unbridgeable schism with Judea's Jewish communities. The geographic position of Samaria between Judea and Galilee made it necessary passage for Jewish pilgrims traveling to Jerusalem, yet the Jew-Samaritan antagonism was so profound that many Jews chose arduous detours rather than passing through Samaritan territory, creating the backdrop for Jesus's parable of the good Samaritan that subversively made a Samaritan the hero showing authentic covenant love compared to Jewish religious leaders. Jesus's encounter with the Samaritan woman at Jacob's well involved revolutionary dialogue breaking multiple cultural taboos (speaking to women, with Samaritans, requesting hospitality from an outsider), while his directive to disciples to take the gospel to Samaria first (Acts 1:8) insisted on the gospel's radical inclusion transcending ancient ethnic animosities.",
